Content:

Once upon a time, there were two Monster Box theists - Lam, the co-founder, and Hieu, one of our motion designers. Once a pious student in religious school, Lam has now been more atheistic than any other atheist.

This article, thus, is to zero in Hieu, along with every argument [on his belief] in our office.

_____

1. A bigoted belief

"Hieu," called Liem, in an any less serious tone, "Do you hold faith in God?"

"Sure I do", politely replied Hieu.

"Cool," said the inquirer before returning to his work.

A while went by before Liem turned to him again, "Still after having worked here for over a year?".

"No question," the latter unflinchingly replied.

"Cool, dude".

"Hieu, still counting on that man upon confessing that your sins are enough to throw you into hell?", then came Phung’s (Hieu's best friend) turn.

"Yep", replied Hieu, again unflinchingly.

"Ain’t it bizarre?" puzzled everyone.

“Were you to be thrown down there, hadn’t you better revere S.a.t.a.n? Should you count on him, who knows he would hold you dear?”, questioned Liem in a still-serious tone.

"...".

"Ever heard of an European man breaking a bread loaf infinitely for everyone’s sake?", joined me.

"Nope".

"Sounds harebrained, huh?".

"Absolutely", replied Hieu.

"Your Jesus played that character".

"..."

"Still holding a faith in him?", every eye stared at him with a question.

"Still".

"After all?"

"After all".

It was when it struck me that Hieu's theism is akin to every other human emotion: given their illogicality, oftentimes we need no reason to either believe or hold dear something.

Until such loves engender some irrational behaviors.

2. What do heaven and hell look like?

"Did the catechism portray heaven?", prompted Liem.

“Yes, albeit somewhat vague. In general, it describes heaven as the best place, wherein we are left with no worries, nor guilts", responded Hieu.

Skimming Wiki, I added: “According to this, the definition of heaven veered over time. It was once a sunny meadow, where people were with God, savoring joy. Then came another period, in which heaven was where the deepest human desires could be satisfied - where wine and food were superabundant and every conflict was done away with”.

"Sounds drearily dull," yelped the rest.

"No wifi?", Minh (a 3D motion designer) rhetorically asked.

"Nah, everything must be well-provided as well; having not preceded the Bible, there was no question that such a  'tucked-away human desire' must have been excluded from the holy book," I commented.

“Still sounding not really appealing either. It would be ecstatic at first, and only at first;” concluded Liem.

“it must be predominated by children, who unfortunately d-i-e early. Pure as they are, there exists no reason for them not going to heaven. Adults, on the other hand, all go to hell”.

"But there must also be some adults to look after children - those having lived so scrupulously that wins them a slot there," Phung purported.

"Some even argue that classism does exist in heaven, for God has his words that he would ‘award’ one in accordance to his ‘life achievement’, the more morally he lives, the more he wins back", commented I, given what I had just read.

"Then come class conflicts, class struggles, and heavenly battles", added Tin (a content writer).

"The more I know it, the less beguiling it is," Minh said.

“It would be more jubilant, were it where people could relive the happiest moments in their lives over and over again, albeit heedless of such a loop. Only then could humans the so-called eternal joy,” Liem proposed his very hypothesis.

"Whilst hell should have been where others relive the most sinful moments," he added.

“Yeah that sounds reasonable, that hell were the very place we got boiled in cauldrons would appear any less marvelous, for sooth. I heard that we are set addicted to that kind of not-to-death torture [as in Black Mirror] ”, Minh could hardly hide his keen interest.

"Cool, then h-e-l-l may be hella fun. By the time Hieu gets thrown down there, he would see the entire Monster Box team already sitting and making science videos for the underworld - there is no question that we are all heading h-e-l-l", giggled I.

“Well, that world bears with cool humans only, from evil younguns to every foolhardy general. Ultimately, it is where we would longer be terror-stricken by death,” then came Phung’s cackle.

"After all, doesn’t hell sound woefully wondrous?," others nodded violently.

After all, however long such conversations might have lasted, however well Hieu heeds that Monster Box would accompany him h-e-l-l, rarely would his faith waver, as always.

3. Does Father report your confessed sins to the police?

"Hieuuuuuuuuu".

"What's the point of confession?", prompted me.

"To either redeem or mitigate your sins", replied Hieu.

"Everything will be okay afterwards?" I was still puzzled.

"Yes, except for deadly sins. Also, confession has its own procedure and you have to appoint beforehand".

"But that makes no sense," yelped others.

"Then should I confess my sins upon having /mɜːdəʳd/ (m-u-r-d-e-r) someone [deliberately transcribed to bypass facebook’s algorithms], they are all done away with?", rarely could I lie low my curiosity.

"At that point, confession is to earn some peace of mind  and accept the very fact that God will turn his back on you", Hieu patiently answered.

"So, were I to mɜːdəʳ someone and confess about which, would Father report it to the police?", prompted Lam.

"..."

"Also, should Father not report it, when the police finds out that he did hear the mɜːdəʳəʳ confess, will he be accused of hiding an actual crime?", Lam couldn’t help digging further.

"That Father can defend that he only listened, and was heedless of the confessor", championed me.

“May a guy confess his crime, expressing the gratitude at his heart being purified afterwards, thus, perpetuating that crime series, will Father report it? Suppose that mɜːdəʳəʳ purposely made a full disclosure so that Father knew his identity”, asked Liem, propelling forward another more specific case.

"He probably will, there is even an emergency button [calling the police] in the confession room," Tin said half jokingly.

"No way, the church system and beliefs would fall apart thereafter," I opposed.

“I reckon that the promise of non-disclosure confession, at first, was honorable, especially during the heyday of religions. But as human civilization advances, civil laws have got reinforced, thus fiercely contradicting religions and ousting which", Liem proposed.

Which is de facto a classic issue. 

There exists the so-called convention of "Seal of Confession" - a sacred promise that the parish priests and the church will never disclose any confession, irregardless of its significance.

History, thence, has witnessed every story on how the commitment was honored, there were even martyrs who refused to give testimony. The Church's view has it that the relationship between the confessor and God is more sacred than any other earthly bond (even the human laws), thus demanding absolute respect.

Nevertheless, in the modern context, where state power soars, unveiling series of church scandals, many countries have imposed laws to coerce churches to break the "Seal”.

4. Less thrilling anecdotes

These conventional discourses, albeit not intentional, may still tick off some religious followers. On my side, I know woefully well that leveraging words and every common human relationship to scrutinize the validity of the Bible, as well as religions, is meaningless and of little value, given their very consistent system wherein arguments may appear unconventional to others.

After all, this article still guarantees authenticity, with the very purpose of portraying the atmosphere and everyday dialogue at Monster Box.

Regarding religious understandings, Liem is even the most knowledgeable person on which. Every so often, his religious insights took me aback. He even helped correct Hieu's understanding, whilst himself coming up with more logical explanations so that Hieu could respond to outsiders in case he gets fiercely questioned (akin to his situation here).

Oftentimes, we chew the rag on religions. “Should we commit crimes on others, causality rules that such wrongdoings hail from some preceding events, instead of my own instinct”, mocked Lam. A life overflooded with sober-mindedness would be grievous, thought I.

Every so often, however, those chats got tense - a small religious argument between Liem and I, for example.

On my side, I propelled that to overthrow the religion reign would be contrary to reason, if the world keeps operating this way. After all, should we scrutinize its nature, the way religion functions vehemently resembles the very models of government, organization, or any other supreme entity. All are abstract social structures. The only difference is the belief they propagate.

By no means is it an innovative view, which has long been dissected among academics. To put it into perspective, even though we often criticize religion for their [bigoted] belief in supernatural, unrealistic entities, the very organizations or states we hold dear still is, albeit earthly, impractical. Neither are objective reality, intangibly prevailing as a common existence in our human imagination. They are only done away with once they have ceased to exist in which.

By the same token, Monster Box - an entity as such - is emerging and woefully gaining credits. Which explains why it exists. Then we can say that such an entity is legally identified and recognized by law - which, should we dig further - is also no less an abstract concept. It dies away as the country of Vietnam dies away. Which only occurs once no human recognizes its existence, given every territorial and ethnic element being kept intact.

The same is true to Monster Box, or any other entity, whose rise and fall are contingent upon how vigorously it is in our human minds.

Holding the same mechanism, religion, thus, is always going hand in hand with society. In a world fueled by beliefs and conventions, new emergences of which is solely a matter of fact. Given the wholesome flat-earth fanclub, there exists no reason for the Creator not having one for his own. That said, religion has so far passed its heyday. In the past, when religion predominated the primitive minds, the church was an unimpeachable force that oftentimes quelled the state government, maneuvering both the military and laws of such societies.

Traces of religion still are tucked away in every non-religious activity, flag salute - for example, in which we hold the very sense of not to “offend the inanimate object” - the flag. Insofar as a person who respects which does not necessarily hold dear religion, he must have never scrutinized his every motive in quavering, or loathing some others insulting the flag - the very representative of his country and people. Rarely had he heeded that before a flag became a flag, it was no less a piece of rag - which is still a rag after it has.

After all, must there be something at its core, a spirit for example, to make it, once sewn in certain proportions and with certain symbols, more sublime than other pieces of rag?

Agreeing that such an operation is popular, Liem, however, also interpreted that it may not essentially engender supernatural beliefs, nor does it earn religions every merit of constituting this world, or of their “home-made immortality”.

So far, the controversies are yet over, akin to many other issues we had previously homed in and squandered quite a long time on which.

All in all, Monster Box, at its core, is religiously diverse, thus, any less openhearted about it, rarely knowing if this openness gets on others’ nerves. Even if it does, we have no other way.

Once upon a time, Lam talked low to Hieu: “Let me reveal a secret to you, everyone has been God-arranged into this office to, after all, defy your belief”.






